Noramay CadenaNoramay Cadena is an engineer and entrepreneur from California. She earned degrees in mechanical engineering and worked in the aerospace industry before turning her focus to business. Now, she supports underrepresented individuals and companies in technology and engineering fields.

Noramay Cadena was born in Mexico and grew up in  Los Angeles, California. Her family had little money. Sometimes they did not have running water or electricity. They also lived in a very supportive community. As a teenager, Noramay worked to help support her family.
Noramay worked hard in school. She excelled in a special science, technology, and math program in high school.

During her junior year, a recruiter encouraged students to apply to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). His words inspired Noramay to apply. When she was accepted, the newspaper ran a story about her accomplishment. Noramay’s parents and members of her community showered her with support. Even people she didn’t know sent her supportive letters and money to help her.
©Curriculum Associates, LLC  Copying is not permitted.UNIT 1  STEM Stories2ST

Noramay identifies problems and perseveres in solving them. As an engineer, she worked hard to solve problems related to building satellites and airplanes. She also perseveres to support others in overcoming barriers to working in STEM fields.
1 	 Think about how Noramay received and gave support. When have others supported you? How do you support others?
2 	 Think about how Noramay perseveres to solve problems. What is a problem you worked hard to solve?
At MIT, Noramay found support. After earning a degree in mechanical engineering, she worked as an engineer on satellites and airplanes.
Now, Noramay supports other people. She helps them get money to start their businesses, and she gives them advice about how to be successful.
Noramay went on to earn advanced degrees in engineering and business. She also started Latinas in STEM, an organization that supports Latinas in STEM careers.

©Curriculum Associates, LLC  Copying is not permitted.LESSON 1  Solve Problems Involving Scale
This week your student is learning about scale drawings. In a scale drawing, the size of an original figure changes, but its shape does not change.
Here are some examples of scale drawings that you may be familiar with.
•  A floor plan is a scale drawing of the actual layout of space in a building.
•  A state road map is a scale drawing of the actual roads in the state.

Scale drawings are typically used when objects are either too small or too large to be shown at their actual sizes. Floor plans and maps are drawn smaller than actual size. Suppose a floor plan is drawn so that 1 inch on the floor plan represents an actual distance of 3 feet. For that floor plan, the scale is 1 in. to 3 ft.
Your student will be solving scale drawing problems like the one below.
The scale from an actual volcano to a drawing of the volcano is 50 m to  5 cm. The height of the drawing of the volcano is 25 cm. How tall is the actual volcano?
➤ONE WAY to find the height is to use a double number line.
➤ANOTHER WAY is to use a scale factor.
The scale from the drawing to the actual volcano is 5 cm for every 50 m, so the
scale factor from the drawing to the volcano is ​ 50 ·· 5 ​ , or 10.
Multiply the height of the model by the scale factor: 25 3 10 5 250.
Using either method, the height of the actual volcano is 250 m.
Use the next page to start a conversation about scale.

Activity Thinking About Scale Around You
➤Do this activity together to investigate scale in the real world.
Have you ever taken a long road trip and come across some large roadside attractions?
The world’s largest cowboy boots are a sculpture in Texas. They are over 35 feet tall! A cowboy boot is normally just 12 inches, or 1 foot, tall.

Gift shops often have models of buildings that fit in the palm of your hand. In Washington, D.C., you can get a Lincoln Memorial model that is 6.5 inches tall. The actual memorial is 80 feet tall! These giant and tiny models are scale copies of real-life objects.
Where do you see scale drawings and scale copies in the world around you?

Look Ahead nD is a scale drawing, or a scale copy, of nA. A scale drawing of a figure is larger or smaller than the original figure but is identical in shape. The scale is the ratio between the side lengths of the original figure and the corresponding side lengths of the scale drawing. To make a scale drawing, you can multiply each length in the original figure by a scale factor to get the corresponding length in the scale drawing. You can think of the scale factor as a unit rate.

➤Study the Example showing how to use a scale drawing to find an actual distance. Then solve problems 1–5.
Colin makes a scale drawing of his bedroom. Every inch in his drawing represents 10 feet in his actual bedroom. The drawing is 1.25 in. wide and 1.5 in. long. How wide and long is his actual bedroom?
You can use a scale factor to find the dimensions.

from the drawing to the bedroom is ​ 10 ·· 1 ​ , or 10.
